"Wilson R., Heinrichs J., Hentschel J., Gradstein S.R., Schneider H.","Steady diversification of derived liverworts under Tertiary climatic fluctuations",2007,"Biology Letters","3","5",,"566","569",,,10.1098/rsbl.2007.0287,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-35549005901&partnerID=40&md5=59f63af383d2bff1dff4f9ca8e9e9ded","Albrecht-von-Haller Institute of Plant Sciences, Georg-August University Göttingen, 37073 Göttingen, Germany; Department of Botany, Natural History Museum, London SW7 5BD, United Kingdom","Wilson, R., Albrecht-von-Haller Institute of Plant Sciences, Georg-August University Göttingen, 37073 Göttingen, Germany; Heinrichs, J., Albrecht-von-Haller Institute of Plant Sciences, Georg-August University Göttingen, 37073 Göttingen, Germany; Hentschel, J., Albrecht-von-Haller Institute of Plant Sciences, Georg-August University Göttingen, 37073 Göttingen, Germany; Gradstein, S.R., Albrecht-von-Haller Institute of Plant Sciences, Georg-August University Göttingen, 37073 Göttingen, Germany; Schneider, H., Albrecht-von-Haller Institute of Plant Sciences, Georg-August University Göttingen, 37073 Göttingen, Germany, Department of Botany, Natural History Museum, London SW7 5BD, United Kingdom","Tropical forests contain the majority of extant plant diversity and their role as a cradle and/or museum of biodiversity is an important issue in our attempts to assess the long-term consequences of global climate change for terrestrial biomes. Highly diverse groups of liverworts are an often ignored but extremely common element in rainforests, and thus their evolution may shed light on the ecological robustness of rainforest biomes to climate fluctuations. We record a remarkable constant accumulation of diversity through time for the most species-rich family of liverworts, Lejeuneaceae, inferred by divergence time estimates. The observed pattern supports the recently developed concept of a dual role of the tropics as both a museum and a cradle of biodiversity. © 2007 The Royal Society.","Divergence time estimates; Lejeuneaceae; Liverworts","article; biodiversity; classification; climate; liverwort; phylogeny; Biodiversity; Climate; Hepatophyta; Phylogeny",,,,,,"Brady, S.G., Schultz, T.R., Fisher, B.L., Ward, P.S., Evaluating alternative hypotheses for the early evolution and diversification of ants (2006) Proc. Natl Acad. Sci. USA, 103, pp. 18172-18177. , doi:10.1073/pnas.0605858103; Bramley, G.L.C., Pennington, R.T., Zakaria, R., Tjitrosoedirdjo, S.S., Cronk, Q.C.B., Assembly of tropical plant diversity on a local scale: Cyrtandra (Gesneriaceae) on Mount Kerinci Sumatra (2004) Biol. J. Linn. Soc., 81, pp. 49-62. , doi:10.1111/j.1095-8312.2004.00283.x; Danforth, B.N., Sipes, S., Fang, J., Brady, S.G., The history of early bee diversification based on five genes plus morphology (2006) Proc. Natl Acad. Sci. USA, 103, pp. 15118-15123. , doi:10.1073/pnas.0604033103; Dimichele, W.A., Philips, T.L., Clades, ecological amplitudes, and ecomorphs: Phylogenetic effects and persistence of primitive plant communities in the Pennsyl-vanian-age tropical wetlands (1996) Palaeogeogr. Palaeoclimatol. Palaeoecol., 127, pp. 83-105. , doi:10.1016/S0031-0182(96) 00089-2; Gradstein, S.R., (1993) Biodiversity and Conservation of Neotropical Montane Forests, p. 21. , eds S. P. Churchill, H. Balslev, E. Forero & J. L. Luteyn New York, NY: The New York Botanical Garden; Gradstein, F., Ogg, J., Smith, A., (2004) A Geologic Time Scale, , Cambridge, UK: Cambridge University Press; Gradstein, S.R., Wilson, R., Ilkiu-Borges, A.L., Heinrichs, J., Phylogenetic relationships and neote-nic evolution of Metzgeriopsis (Lejeuneaceae) based on chloroplast DNA sequences and morphology (2006) Bot. J. Linn. Soc., 151, pp. 293-308. , doi:10.1111/j.1095-8339.2006.00531.x; Grolle, R., Meister, K., (2004) The Liverworts in Baltic and Bitterfeld Amber, , Jena, Germany: Weissdorn; Heinrichs, J., Hentschel, J., Wilson, R., Feldberg, K., Schneider, H., Evolution of le